{{Expand French|date=July 2011|Sarvangasana}} {{IndicText}} [[File:Sarvangâsana.jpg|thumb|right|Salamba Sarvangasana]] '''Sarvangasana''' ({{IPAc-en|ˌ|s|ɑːr|v|ɑː|n|ˈ|ɡ|ɑː|s|ɑː|n|ɑː}} {{respell|SAR|vahn|GAH|sah|nah}}<ref>{{cite book |last1=Budilovsky |first1=Joan |last2=Adamson |first2=Eve |title=The complete idiot's guide to yoga |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b5pE8-Oyly0C |accessdate=11 April 2011 |edition=2 |year=2000 |publisher=Penguin |isbn=978-0-02-863970-3 |page=174}}</ref> {{lang-sa|सर्वाङ्गासन}}; [[IAST]]: ''sarvāṅgāsana''; {{IPA-sa|sərʋəŋgɑːsənə|pron}}) or '''Shoulderstand''' is an [[asana|āsana]].
Many variations of the shoulderstand exist, the likely most common to be taught is Supported Shoulderstand (Salamba Sarvangāsana).<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.yogajournal.com/poses/480 | title = Yoga Journal - Supported Shoulderstand | accessdate = 11 April 2011}}</ref>
Sarvangāsana is nicknamed "queen" or "mother" of all the asanas.<ref name="Francina2003">{{cite book |last=Francina |first=Suza |title=Yoga and the Wisdom of Menopause: A Guide to Physical, Emotional and Spiritual Health at Midlife and Beyond |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CMl_IiCoCRYC&pg=PA233 |accessdate=11 April 2011 |date=23 March 2003 |publisher=HCI |isbn=978-0-7573-0065-3 |page=233}}</ref><ref name="NorbergLundberg2008">{{cite book |last1=Norberg |first1=Ulrica |last2=Lundberg |first2=Andreas |title=Hatha Yoga: The Body's Path to Balance, Focus, and Strength |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IvIFC8Tbe24C&pg=PA106 |accessdate=11 April 2011 |date=8 April 2008 |publisher=Skyhorse Publishing Inc. |isbn=978-1-60239-218-2 |page=106}}</ref><ref name="KappmeierAmbrosini2006">{{cite book |last1=Kappmeier |first1=Kathy Lee |last2=Ambrosini |first2=Diane M. |title=Instructing hatha yoga |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K5WaYzBYypkC&pg=PA265 |accessdate=11 April 2011 |year=2006 |publisher=Human Kinetics |isbn=978-0-7360-5209-2 |page=265}}</ref>
==Etymology== The name in the case of '''Salamba Sarvāngāsana''' (Supported Shoulderstand) comes from the Sanskrit words ''Salamba'' meaning "supported", ''Sarva'' meaning "all" or "every", ''Anga'' meaning "limb" or "bodypart",<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ashtangayoga.info/practice/asana-vinyasa-series/the-finishing-sequence/item/salamba-sarvangasana/ | title = Salamba Sarvangāsana - AshtangaYoga.info | accessdate = 11 April 2011}}</ref> and ''Āsana'' meaning "posture"," position", or "seat",<ref name="Sinha1996">{{cite book|last=Sinha|first=S.C.|title=Dictionary of Philosophy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-zzRvh1fRzEC&pg=PA18|accessdate=9 April 2011|date=1 June 1996|publisher=Anmol Publications PVT. LTD.|isbn=978-81-7041-293-9|page=18}}</ref> thus Salamba Sarvāngasana literally translates to "supported-all-limbs-pose".
