'''Xuefeng Yicun''' (822-908) ({{zh|s=雪峰义存|w=Hsüeh-feng I-ts'un}}; {{zh|p=Xuěfēng Yìcún}}; {{Nihongo|Seppō Gison}}) was a [[Chinese Chán|Chinese Chan-master]] who was influential during the [[Tang Dynasty]]. The [[Yunmen school]] and [[Fayan school]] originated with descendants of his lineage.

==Biography==
According to the ''Wudeng Huiyuan'' ("Compendium of Five Lamps"){{sfn|Ferguson|2011}} Xuefeng Yicun was born in 822 in Nanan in ancient the district Quanzhou (now the province of [[Fujian]]). At age twelve he left home to live at Yujian Temple in Putian City.{{sfn|Ferguson|2011}}

During the [[Chinese Chán#The Great Persecution|suppression of Buddhism]] (841-846) by [[Emperor Xuānzong of Tang|Emperor Xuanzong]] Xuefeng Yicun was forced to leave the monastery. He continued his apprenticeship with a master Yuanzhao (Changzhao) on top of Furong (Lotus) Mountain in [[Hunan]].{{sfn|Welter|2006|p=92}}

When Emperor Xuanzong allowed for the restoration of Buddhism Xuefeng started hiking in the different regions of northern China.{{sfn|Welter|2006|p=92}} He received the full ordination of monks in 850 in the Baocha monastery in [[Youzhou]] (now Beijing) in the [[Hebei]] province.{{sfn|Ferguson|2011}}

Later he went to Wuling (near the modern city of Changde in Hunan province), and became a student and dharma heir of [[Deshan Xuanjian]] (782-865).{{sfn|Ferguson|2011}}

After his awakening Xuefeng returned to his former monastery on top of the Lotus Mountain,{{sfn|Welter|2006|p=94}} and then built a monastery on the top of Guangfu Xuefeng (Snow Summit) Top Xianggu (Elephant Bone).{{sfn|Ferguson|2011}} During the ''qianfu'' era (874-878) the monastery was officially recognized by the authorities. His teachings were supported by several officials in the Min region. As a result of his growing fame, Xuefeng was summoned to the court by palace officials. Xuefeng was awarded a purple robe and the title of "Grand Master of the truly enlightened" (''zhenjue dashi'') (or Grand Master of the True Enlightenment) by [[Emperor Xizong of Tang|Emperor Xizong]].{{sfn|Welter|2006|p=94}}

In 891 Xuefeng went to travel again. In 892 he had joined the attendants of [[Yang Xingmi]], the ruler of the newly established [[Wu (Ten Kingdoms)|Wu (Jiangshi)]] regime, "cleansing soldiers with dharma-rain and performing ceremonies at Chan monasteries".{{sfn|Welter|2006|p=94}} This strengthened his reputation "as a Buddhist prelate who administered to the needs of local rulers".{{sfn|Welter|2006|p=94}} In 894 he returned to the Min region, where he was supported by [[Wang Chao (Tang Dynasty)|Wang Xu]]{{sfn|Welter|2006|p=94}} (r.891-897).{{sfn|Welter|2006|p=96}}  Wang Xu was followed by his brother [[Wang Shenzhi]] (r.897-925), under whose reign Buddhism became established in the Min region. Xuefeng had become a state prelate, who had a central role in promoting Buddhism,{{sfn|Welter|2006|p=96}} and who had to spread his influence throughout the entire region.{{sfn|Welter|2006|p=94}}

==Teachings==
The ''Runei lun fo xinjin lu'' ("Record of Discussions in the Palace regarding the Buddha Mind-seal") records his conversations with Wang Shenzhi.{{sfn|Welter|2006|p=96}} It is "highly reminiscent of earlied Chan precedents, particularly Bodhidharma's renunciation of the Liang emperor Wu recorded in the ''Platform sutra''.{{sfn|Welter|2006|p=98}} The records seem to be modelled according to the examples of Bodhidharma and Huineng.{{sfn|Welter|2006|p=99}}

Xuefeng's Chán-style was similar to that of [[Mazu Daoyi]].{{sfn|Wu|2011|p=204}}{{sfn|Welter|2006|p=99}} The phrase "Mind is Buddha", used by Xuefeng, was "allegedly introduced into Chan circles in the teaching attributed to Mazu Daoyi".{{sfn|Welter|2006|p=99}} But the same teaching is also attributed to Shitou.

==Influence and lineage==
Xuefeng was one of the most influential Chán-teachers at the end of the Tang Dynasty,{{sfn|McRae|2003|p=13}} when "a widely influential zen center formed around Xuefeng Yicun".{{sfn|Dumoulin|2005a|p=169}} The loss of control by the Tang Dynasty, and the accompanying loss of support for Buddhist institutions, lead to a regionally based Chan of Xuefeng and his students.{{sfn|Welter|2006|p=90}}

===Students===
Xuefeng Yicun was the teacher of [[Yunmen Wenyan]] (862 or 864–949 CE), who established the [[Yunmen school]]. [[Fayan Wenyi]] (885-958), Xuefeng's "grand-disciple", established the [[Fayan school]].{{sfn|Jones|2010}}

Xuansha Shibei (WG Hsüan-sha Shih-pei) (835-908), a student of Xuefeng Yicun, is cited by [[Wumen Huikai]] (WG Wu-men Hui-k'ai, Jpn. Mumon Ekai) in explaining the title of his famous koan-collection, the ''[[Mumonkan]]'' ("Gateless barrier"), in explaining the title of this collection: 
{{quote|Have you not heard what Hsüan-sha said, 'No-gate is the gate of emancipation; no-mind is the mind of the man of Tao'?{{sfn|Dumoulin|2005a|p=251}}}}

===Zutang ji===
The ''[[Anthology of the Patriarchal Hall|Zutang ji]]'' (祖堂集 "Anthology of the Patriarchal Hall), compiled in 952, the first document which mentions [[Linji Yixuan]], was written to support the Xuefeng Yicun lineage.{{sfn|Welter|year unknown-B}} It pictures this lineage as heir to the legacy of Mazu and the Hongzhou-school,{{sfn|Welter|year unknown-B}} though Xuefeng Yicun's lineage is traced back to [[Shitou Xiqian]] (700-790). It was written by two students of Zhaoqing Wendeng (884-972), a dharma descendant of Xuefeng Yicun.

